      <section id="legal-rights">
        <h2>Legal Rights for Women in India</h2>
        <p>
          Women in India are protected under several legal provisions aimed at
          ensuring their safety and well-being. These laws empower women to seek
          justice and provide legal recourse in case of violence, harassment, or
          discrimination.
        </p>
        <h3>Key Laws Protecting Women:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong
              >Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005:</strong
            >
            This law protects women from abuse by family members, including
            physical, emotional, and economic violence.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Criminal Law Amendment Act, 2013:</strong> Introduced
            stricter punishment for sexual harassment, stalking, acid attacks,
            and trafficking.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Sexual Harassment of Women at Workplace Act, 2013:</strong>
            Protects women from harassment at the workplace and ensures a safe
            working environment.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961:</strong> Prohibits the giving
            or taking of dowry during marriage and makes it punishable by law.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Indian Penal Code (IPC) Provisions:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Section 354:</strong> Protects women from acts of
                molestation.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Section 376:</strong> Provides severe punishment for
                rape, ensuring justice for survivors.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Section 509:</strong> Covers verbal abuse and
                inappropriate gestures.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="helplines">
        <h2>Helplines and Emergency Services</h2>
        <p>
          The government has provided several helplines and emergency services
          specifically for women in distress. These services are available 24/7
          to ensure timely assistance.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Women Helpline Number (1091):</strong> A dedicated helpline
            number for women facing harassment or violence.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>National Emergency Number (112):</strong> An integrated
            emergency number for police, ambulance, and fire services.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Police Helpline (100):</strong> For immediate police
            assistance.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Women’s Safety Mobile App (1091 App):</strong> A mobile
            application by the government where women can register complaints,
            seek help, and access safety features like tracking and SOS
            messaging.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="safety-guidelines">
        <h2>Safety Guidelines for Women</h2>
        <h3>At Home:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Ensure that doors and windows are securely locked, especially during
            the night.
          </li>
          <li>
            Always verify the identity of visitors or service personnel through
            proper identification cards or references.
          </li>
          <li>Install security cameras or alarms for added safety.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>In Public Spaces:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Stay in well-lit areas, especially at night.</li>
          <li>
            Avoid accepting lifts from strangers, especially in secluded areas.
          </li>
          <li>Keep emergency contacts on speed dial.</li>
          <li>
            Use mobile apps with GPS tracking to alert family members in case of
            an emergency.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>In the Workplace:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Be aware of workplace policies regarding harassment and
            discrimination.
          </li>
          <li>
            Report any instance of inappropriate behavior to the Internal
            Complaints Committee (ICC) in your organization.
          </li>
          <li>
            Never hesitate to speak up or seek legal help if facing harassment
            at work.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="cyber-safety">
        <h2>Cyber Safety for Women</h2>
        <p>
          With the increasing use of the internet and social media, women must
          take precautions to protect their online privacy.
        </p>
        <h3>Key Guidelines:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Avoid sharing personal information such as addresses or contact
            details on social media.
          </li>
          <li>
            Regularly update passwords and enable two-factor authentication for
            online accounts.
          </li>
          <li>
            Be cautious of unknown messages or emails asking for personal or
            financial information.
          </li>
          <li>
            Use privacy settings to control who can view your online profiles.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Legal Provisions for Cyber Safety:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>The Information Technology Act, 2000:</strong> Protects
            women from cybercrimes like hacking, online harassment, and identity
            theft.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Section 67A of the IT Act:</strong> Deals with the
            transmission of obscene material online.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Cyber Crime Helpline (155260):</strong> A helpline for
            reporting online harassment and cybercrimes.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="government-initiatives">
        <h2>Government Initiatives for Women’s Safety</h2>
        <p>
          Several government programs have been launched to promote women’s
          safety in various spheres of life.
        </p>
        <h3>Key Initiatives:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>One Stop Centre Scheme (OSC):</strong> Provides integrated
            support and assistance to women affected by violence, including
            medical, legal, and psychological help.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Beti Bachao, Beti Padhao:</strong> A national initiative
            aimed at protecting and empowering the girl child.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mahila Police Volunteers:</strong> Women police volunteers
            work in communities to ensure safety, provide guidance, and raise
            awareness about women's rights.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Nirbhaya Fund:</strong> A fund created for initiatives to
            enhance the safety and security of women in the country.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="reporting-crimes">
        <h2>How to Report Crimes Against Women</h2>
        <p>
          It is essential to understand the steps involved in reporting crimes
          against women:
        </p>
        <h3>Steps to File a Complaint:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Approach the nearest police station or file an online FIR through
            the
            <a href="https://digitalpolice.gov.in/" target="_blank"
              >National Crime Reporting Portal</a
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            If the police refuse to file an FIR, you can approach the
            <strong>District Superintendent of Police</strong> or file a
            complaint before a <strong>Magistrate</strong>.
          </li>
          <li>Helplines like 1091 can be used to report crimes anonymously.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
